This indiscriminateness of hospitality is characteristic of ancient civilization‚ and grows out of its circumstances: without it, travelling would have been impossible. It can be illustrated abun- dantly from the Homeric poems, and from many other sources, and has its counterpart now in scantily peopled countries, though in strong contrast to modern society generally, or to the Rome of Tacitus.
